    {
      "id": 21,
      "date": "2021-02-12",
      "type": "visit_note",
      "doctor": "Dr. Michael Torres",
      "department": "Cardiology",
      "summary": "AMIODARONE-INDUCED HYPOTHYROIDISM CONFIRMED",
      "content": "70 y/o male. TSH 18.4, free T4 0.5 \u00e2\u20ac\u201d overt hypothyroidism. Amiodarone is a well-known cause (contains 37% iodine by weight, disrupts thyroid hormone synthesis). This explains the past 6+ months of symptoms: fatigue, weight gain (+8 lbs), cold intolerance, constipation, dry skin, periorbital puffiness, rising cholesterol (248, was 178), and bradycardia (HR 56). MONITORING FAILURE: Thyroid function should have been checked every 6 months on amiodarone \u00e2\u20ac\u201d was checked at baseline only (Feb 2020) and not again until now (Feb 2021). This means hypothyroidism has been developing for months without detection. Assessment: Amiodarone-induced hypothyroidism. Plan: Start levothyroxine 50mcg daily (cautious dose given cardiac history). DO NOT stop amiodarone \u00e2\u20ac\u201d needed for AFib control. Recheck TSH in 6-8 weeks. Endocrinology referral for co-management."
    },
